# C++ Kernel Coding Standards

## Freestanding Environment

- Use `-ffreestanding -fno-exceptions -fno-rtti` compiler flags
- Do not include hosted headers (`<iostream>`, `<vector>`, etc.) — use `<stdint.h>`, `<stddef.h>`, `<stdarg.h>` only
- Implement custom `memcpy`, `memset`, `memmove` if needed

## Memory Management

- All heap allocation must go through a custom allocator — never call `new`/`delete` without a backing allocator
- Document ownership semantics in function signatures (who allocates, who frees)
- Prefer stack allocation and fixed-size buffers in interrupt/exception handlers

## Style

- Use fixed-width types (`uint32_t`, `uintptr_t`) instead of `int`/`long` for hardware-facing code
- Name registers, MMIO offsets, and hardware constants with `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE`
- Prefix architecture-specific symbols: `x86_`, `arm_`, `arch_`
- Keep ISR / interrupt handlers as short as possible — defer work to a bottom-half or task queue

## Error Handling

- No C++ exceptions — use return codes or a `Result<T, E>` style wrapper
- Kernel panics should print diagnostics to the framebuffer/serial before halting

## Example — fixed-width types and no exceptions

```cpp
// BAD
int read_port(int port) {
  throw std::runtime_error("fail");
}

// GOOD
uint8_t x86_inb(uint16_t port) {
  uint8_t result;
  asm volatile("inb %1, %0" : "=a"(result) : "Nd"(port));
  return result;
}
```
